{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2goncharova_ver03/data/sn83045462/00280605165/1948120201/0628.xml":{"full_text":"New Administration\nIs Anxious to Have\nBusiness Viewpoint\nIndustry Leaders Urged\nTo Take More Interest\nIn Government Policies\nBy David Lawrence\nBusinessmen, many of whom have\nbeen Buffering from the shock of\nthe election result and some of\nwhom have gotten the mistaken im\npression that their advice isn\u2019t\nwanted in Washington, are being\ntold to forget it\u2014and come and\nmake their viewpoints known.\nThe Truman administration has\ntaken cognizance of the wave of pes\nsimism which recently swept the\nbusiness community. Secretary of\nCommerce Sawyer went to particu\nlar pains to write this week a public\naddress, which he submitted to\nPresident Truman, assuring business\nthat there is no plot afoot to under\nmine the economic system with de\nstructive legislation.\nSimilar expressions of reassur\nance may be forthcoming. The truth\nis that the administration is much\nsurprised at the reaction in some\nbusiness quarters over the expecta\ntion of a sudden turn to radicalism.\nPossibly much of the talk in busi\nness circles stems from the out\nspoken predictions of an intent to\nwipe out the Taft-Hartley law and\nleave the one-sided Wagner Act in\nits place. Another source of con\ncern is the proposal to restore the\nwartime excess-profits law.\nViews Not Crystallized.\nOn both these counts the adminis\ntration views have by no means\ncrystallized. While it is certain that\na law which will bear the names of\nDemocrats instead of Republicans\nwill replace the Taft-Hartley Act, it\nIs not so certain that the one-sided\nWagner law will be that substitute.\nEven if the labor leaders want such\nan extreme position, the adminis\ntration knows that such a proposal\nwill not get by Congress, where a\nmajority who voted for the Taft\nHartley Act is still in powrer. What\never law is passed will have to take\naccount of the conflicting interests\nof labor unions and management.\nIn the end, there will be repeal only\nIf such a compromise is developed.\nTo put it another way, the advo\ncates of outright repeal without a\nsubstitute will be playing into the\nhands of those who want the Taft\nHartley Act to go untouched.\nOn excess-profits taxes. Senator\nO\u2019Mahoney, one of the most power\nful of the Democrats in the Senate,\ntold the press after a visit to the\nPresident that an actual restoration\nof the wartime law on excess profits\nwas not contemplated. He spoke of\nthe need for writing a law that\nwould not discourage new enter\nprises. This reveals an awareness\nof the whole problem of siphoning\nStrictly Cold Protocol\nTop Officials Seen Acting to Chill\nAny Propaganda by Mme. Chiang\nBy Doris Fleeson\nMadame Chiang Kai-shek arrived\nhere on the coldest day of the sea\nson. literally and diplomatically.\nThe White House and State De\npartment routed\nher strictly*\nthrough chan\nnels with the H\nprecise amount I\nof attention ex- I\nacted by proto-\ncol. Then they s\nstudiously dead-\npanned q u e s\ntions about her\nvisit in a man\nner clearly de\nsigned to chill\nany propaganda\ndrive that may j\nbe in the mak\ning.\nUorii FI\u00ab\u00bbon.\nI it is understood also that un\nofficial circles interested in China\nhave had the word passed to them\nthat this is no time for great public\noutcries on the Chinese crisis.\nCan't Hide Facts.\nFor a few days Mme. Chiang will\nenlov the Southern hospitality and\nwomanlv sympathy of Mrs. George\nc. Marshall at the Marshall home\nat Leesburg, Va. They will not\nhide from her acute political sense\nseveral facts.\nOne is the absence of her host,\nthe Secretary of State, who is offi\ncially described as in Walter Reed\nHospital for a physical checkup.\nPresiding at a press conference a\nfew hours after Mme. Chiang's ar\nrival, Undersecretary of State Lpvett\nwas extremely detached about the\nWhole matter. He couldn\u2019t add any\nthing to the Walter Reed bulletin\nand he hadn't heard anything di\nrectl.v about a possible conference\nwith Mme. Chiang at the State De\npartment.\nIn the White House, Press Secre\ntary Ross conceded that there was\nprobably a country called China but\nlittle more. He had no idea- when\nMme. Chiang might call on Presi\ndent Truman.\nEconomic Co-operation Adminis\ntrator Hoffman heralded her ar\nrival with an announcement that he\nwill take off Friday for his own\nlook at China, arriving in Shanghai\nDecember 11.\nThat Mme. Chiang's political an\ntennae have already picked up these\nsignals appears from tier brief state\nment at Leesburg for the newsreels.\nShe thanked her American friends\nand pleaded for \u201ca little time\u201d to\nrecover her equilibrium after her\nlong fli|ht.\nDifficult Problem.\nTechnically her problem is a diffi\ncult one. There is one powerful\ncourt of appeal from executive cool\nness in Washington and that is the\nCongress, which has power of its\nown and constitutes a wonderful\nforum for arousing public opinion\nBut Congress is not in session and\nduring the pre-Christmas interval\nfew members visit the Capital, pre\nferring to enjoy their last few weeks\nat home before the long session\nbegins.\nWith the prospective chairmen of\nthe Foreign Relations Committees,\nshe has scored about 50-50. Rep\nresentative Bloom kindly said he\nthought the House ought to heat\nher; Senator Connally was gruff\nabout what he considered her hus\nband's failing as a national leader.\nThe hardened official temper to\nward China is given a simple, harsh\nexplanation in State Department\nquarters. It is attributed to a belief\nthat measures short of war cannot\nalter the situation materially, and\nno one believes any risk of war will\nbe taken. Nobody seems either very\ndefinite about United States policy\ntoward China nor very pleased\nabout it; they have acquired only\nthe definite opinion that not much\ncan be done now.\noff into tax receipts any excess of\n'profits without disturbing businesses\njin the growth stage. Mere percent\nage rates will not be of avail and\n.could conceivably impair the whole\neconomic structure. Some other\n'formula has to be devised\u2014and it\nis not easy. But the fact that the\nadministration indicates that it\nknows the complexity of the prob\nlem is reassuring in itself.\nCo-operation Needed.\nMore important than any other\nphase of the postelection mood of\nj business is the report that some\nbusinessmen feel they have been\n'cut off from Washington and that\n'they should avoid the National\nCapital as much as possible. This\nj is probably not an accuarte reflec\njtion at all of how the majority of\ni businessmen feel, but the report\nhas gained ground here recently,\nespecially as It has been asserted\nthat some businessmen expect the\nTruman administration, by radical\nlegislation, involuntarily to create\nconditions that will bring about a\nrecession, and hence a political up\nheaval would result and a Repub\nlican Congress would come back in\n1950.\nThe situation internationally is so\nserious that any holding back or\nreluctance by any economic group\nto co-operate in Washington just\nnow can be Injurious. The co\noperation of every group is needed\nto make the economic system func\ntion on a voluntary basis, with Gov\nernment as a guide to what consti\ntutes the public interest.\nIf a recession does come, there\nis always the possibility that a much\nmore radical Congress may be\nelected in 1950 and that national\nization or some new forms of control\nof industry and business may result.\nBusinessmen who let the forming\nof policies here go by default will\nbe making a serious mistake. The\nadministration is anxious to have\nthe business viewpoint as well as\nthe labor or agricultural viewpoint.\nIt is a time for greater rather than\nless Interest in Government and\nmore rather than less participation\nby businessmen in the councils of\nthose here who make governmental\npolicy on economic questions.\n(Reproduction Rights Reserved.)\nGLEN ELEN\u2019S\nPRE-CHRISTMAS\nMEN\u2019S SUITS\nFrom Our Regular 69.50 Stock\nMen! Here ii our Christmas gift to you!\nSave $15 on every one of these quality\nready-made suits, made In our own\nshop. Worsteds, flannels and gobardines\nin browns, blues, groys. Single dr double\nbreasted, in sizes 35 to 44. regulars\nand a few shorts.\nGABARDINE TOPCOATS\nRegularly 59.50_ *44.50\nCompanion sole! All purpose coot of\n100% wool gobordine, water repellent.\nSet-in sleeves. Regulars, longs and short*.\n(&lm Alnt\nCUSTOM TAILORS\n1402 New York Avc. N.W.\nSterling 4155\nOpen Thursday and\nFriday Nights to 9\nBRIGGS\u2019 4\nARE 4\nTWICE\nAS GOOD!\nEver notice that when franks are served, they\ncome in pairs? No wonder, when most franks\nserved are Briggs'! 'Bout the only dish tastier\nthan Briggs' Better Franks is another portion\u2014\nthey taste twice as good. Let your family see\ndouble tonight! Serve tasty delicious Briggs'\nfor a double treat.\nFor Goodness For Flavor For Economy\nBRIGGS\u2019 BETTER FRANKS\nCopyright ltt/t, Briggt A Co.\nLOUIE\n\u2014By Harry Hanan\nIll\nforget\nYOUR FOOT I\nTROUBLE G\n*E*R OVK.'-f\nXOMfY\u2019 S\nSHOES\nCOMPLAINTS\ny\nW\nswc\n'rr^r-NSTTWAWTO^Bg;\nOn the Other Hand\nMembers of Our Highest Court\nRetain Their Rights as Citizens\nBy Lowell Mellett\nThey\u2019re Riving Bill Douglas the\ndickens, some people are, for mak\ning a speech to the CIO annual con\nvention in Portland, Oreg., last\nweek. By Bi.l\nDouglas I mean 1\nthe Hon. Wil\nliam Orville\nDouglas, Asso\nciate Justice of\nthe United\nStates Supreme\nCourt.\nTire people\nnow' criticizing\nhim think of\nhim only as the\nHonorable, etc.,\nnot as Bill. But\nactually it is the\nsame person, the\nsame Bill who\nLowell Mellett.\nlived in a tent on a vacant lot in\nWalla Walla, Wash., while putting\nhimself through college there by\nwashing windows and waiting on\ntable in a hash house; who took\ntime out to be a soldier in World\nWar I. but finished college as presi\ndent of the student body; who wet\nnursed a carload of sheep to pay his\n[fare east to Columbia Law School,\nworked his way through that insti\ntution and finished second in his\n[class and editor of the Columbia\nLawr Review; who came to^Wash\nington to make a remarkable rec\ni ord as head of the Securities and\nExchange Commission and was ap\npointed, the youngest member, of\nthe Supreme Court 10 years ago.\nQualified to Speak.\nNobody, measured by experience,\ni is better qualified to talk to labor\nconcerning labor's place in the mod\nem world, nobody better justified\nin expounding his personal philos\nSTORM DOORS\nCombinotions. (Closed Sots.)\nRUCKER LUMBER\n1320 Wilson Blvd.. Arl. CH. 0680\nNigbtCoagfo\ndue to colds...eased\nwithout \"dosing\u201d\n1\nMm-m Scrumptious with\nOld Plantation Syrup\n1 cup syrup M cup butter\nHeat and beat together.\nServe hot over\nAUNT JEMIMA BUCKWHEATS\nJust add milk or water.\n'^KINDS'\ntom Jemima\nBIM0T-MIX t J\nUwamtim\ni Thn rad box\nfor Pancokat\nand Wafflai,\nme yellow box for tuckwheoh with\nf-u-t-t the right amount of real\nbuckwheat Mover I\n>-__\nophy concerning the fix the world\nis in.\nHe is being criticized, not so much\nfor what he said\u2014although some of\nhis critics do not like his forthright,\nclassless conception of democracy\u2014\nbut because he said it while a mem\nber of the country's highest court.\nHe is being told that he should not\nhave \u201cstepped down\" from the\nbench to take part in mundane af\nfairs. This, it seems to me, is a bit\nof sanctimonious nonsense.\nWhen a man accepts appointment\nto the Supreme Court, he doesn't\nthereby cease to be a citizen. That\nis true whether he has previously\ndevoted his.talents to public service\nor to the private practice of corpo\nration law. He retains his right to\nvote and, by the same token, to\nspeak his mind. In most State\ncourts, including State supreme\ncourts, he is permitted by law and\ncustom to campaign for election and\nfor re-election. This doesn't, or\nshouldn\u2019t, lessen his capacity for\njudicial service. After all, his job as\na judge is simply to determine the\nmerits of the contentions brought\nbefore him and to apply the law as\nit is written; or, in the case of Fed\neral judges, sometimes to rule on\nthe constitutionality of the law it\nself. In exercising the latter func\ntion he is expected to give his in\ntelligence and knowledge to the in\nterpretation of the Constitution as\nit is, not as he thinks it should be.\nThere could be no proper quarrel,\n-indeed, with a judge who argued, on\nthe bench or off, that the Constitu\ntion should be amended, so long as\nhe confined his official decisions to\nthe Constitution as it is.\nTime for Thinking.\nThis is not a stuffed-shirt period\nin history. It is one that calls for\nMcLemore\u2014\nThinks It's Time\nTo Learn English\nBy Henry McLemore\nHONOLULU Tomorrow, after\nfive months of longitudin\u2019 and\nlatitudin\u2019 around the thing Chris\ntopher Columbus proved was round,\nI am leaving lor\nthe United;\nStates.\nIn prepara\ntion for my re- f\nturn to my na\ntive soil, I am 4\ngoing to take 1\nAmerican 1 e s\nsons\u2014lessons i n\nhow to speak\nEnglish as\nAmericans do.\nIt is surpris\ning what a\nworld trip will\ndo to an igno\nrant man. Every\nHenry McLemore.\ntime he gets to a new foreign coun\ntry, he has to make his wants\nknown in a ridiculous form of pid\ngin English.\nHow It\u2019s Done.\nThis is done by raising the voice,\nstanding on tiptoe and shouting the\nword that you want the foreigner\nto understand. Also, each word\nis spoken slowly, as if you Uere\naddressing a 3-year-old child. For\nexample, when I wanted ice water\nin India, I asked for it this way:\n\u201cPlease bring me ice water.\" It\nsounded roughly like an Indian\nchief in the early days of America\ntalking to Kit Carson or Daniel\nBoone. When I wanted to know a\ndirection. I raised my voice to\nlocomotive whittle pitch and spoke\nhard thinking and for the participa\ntion of the world's best minds. That\nWilliam O. Douglas has one of those\nminds has been generally agreed for\na good many years, and if he has\nbeen engaged in some hard think\ning concerning the problems that\nbeset the world, there is no reason,\nin all good sense, why he should be\nbashful about expressing himself.\nBut. it is said, he shouldn't have\nappeared before a labor convention\n'to air the results of his thinking.\nPresumably, if it had been a con\nvention of teachers or merchants or\ngadget manufacturers, it would have\nbeen all right; if it had been a con\nvention of lawyers, it definitely\nwould have been considered all right,\nbecause members of the high court\nfrequently address bar associations.\nThe logic of this is hard to follow,\nsince lawyers do business directly\nwith the courts.\nNo, it is said, the point is that\nlabor is now in politics. Well, who\nisn't? Everybody certainly should\nbe. Labor is in politics and has be\ncome important in politics.\n\"Today,\u201d said Justice Douglas,\n\"labor has it within its power to\nguide western civilization, neither\nto the right nor to the left, but down\nthe broad middle highway to abun\nI dance, to security, and to peace.\u201d\nIf the Justice thinks that, why\nshould he leave it unsaid?\nI <Copyright 1949, Globe Syndicate.)\nto the Siamese, Turk or Chinese\nin this manner: \"How do I get from\nhere to the Green Lantern Restau\nrant?\u201d For some reason, if you\nspeak English loudly enough and\nslowly enough, all the peoples of\nthe world understand it.\nWhen I reached Honolulu, which\nis part of the United States and a\nplace where every one speaks English\nas they do in Cleveland, Dallas* and\nBoston, I kept talking to 'em as if\nthey were people in far away lands.\nI walked into a drugstore in Hono\nlulu and drew amazed looks from\nthe Americans when I said. \"Would\nyou make me milk shake? Milk\nshe come from big animals with\nhorns.\u201d Then, with gestures, I\ndemonstrated the process of milking\na cow so he would understand. The\nsoda jerker, who had worked two\nyears in New York before he went'\nto Honolulu, asked me if I were\ncrazy. \"Lissen, Bub. do you want a\nmilk shake? Do you want an egg\nin it? Do you want chocolate,\nvanilla, raspberry or coffee? What\never you want, ask for it in Enelish.\u201d\n\"You no understand,\u201d I said. \u201cI\nbeen away from country long time.\nI got habit talking this way foreign.\"\n\"You better get straightened out,\nJoe, before you go home,\" the soda\njerk said. \"You're back home and\ndon't know it.\u201d\nTo Enter Kindergarten.\nSo, this afternoon I will enroll\nin .the Honolulu kindergarten class.\nI went direct to Nat Norfleet's store\nand bought a sturdy pair of Buster\nBrown shoes, a pair of blue flannel\nknickers and some little socks. Also,\na white shirt and a nice little tie.\nBetween the hours of three and five,\nI should be busy at the blackboard\nwith my chalk, learning once again\nhow to speak the language of my\ncountry without puncturing the ear\ndrums of those two, three and some\ntimes even four blocks away.\nI want to be able to go into a\ndrugstore when I get home and\norder a double banana split with\nout having those present gaze at\nme and say. \u201cI wish our immigra\ntion laws were not so lax\nHow does one behave in kinder\ngarten when he ne\u2019ds a shave? Do\nthey provide razors with the- bv 'cl\ning blocks? I don\u2019t want to be\nthrown out of school because of five\no'clock shadow.\n'Distributed by McNaught Syndicate. Ine.)\nYou'll need something made\nof flour to make each\nmeal complete!\n_-way\nnourishment\nNo other food gives you such o\nwholesome combination of good\nfood os do the things made of\nflour. The flour, the milk, eggs,\nsugar and other good things thot\npies, cakes, rolls, bread, etc., are\nmode with make delicious foods\nmighty good for you,\nas well as wonderfully\ngood eating. ^5\nrn\nFOR SALE AT ALL FOOD STORES\nOFFERS SUCH\nLIBERAL TRADE-IN\nON YOUR OLD REFRIGERATOR FOR A\nBrand-new, Latest Model 1949\nCROSLEY\nJUST IN TIME FOR CHRISTMAS\n8 CUBIC\nFEET\nCAPACITY\nONLY SHELVADOR HASi\nExtra Front Row Food Space\nDouble Crispors\nRoomy Food Compartment\nHugo loo Cube Capaeity\nNon-Tipping Shelves\nTOTAL $239.95\nMODEL M-88\nyour old, tired\nice box just\nhas to go\u2014 i\nGet the most I\nfor it. GOTO I\nALPERSTEIN\u2019S\n1020 7th St. N.W.\nNA. 8559\n1023 7th St. N.W.\nNA. 8559\nDEPARTMENT STORES\n224 Carroll Ave., Takoma Park\nSH. 2700","height":"31972","width":"22272"}}
